I"<p>If <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/body-seeks-homeostasis">stress</a> triggers special <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/metabolism-influences-neural-dynamics">metabolic</a> prioritization patterns, then prolonged periods of stress result in usual demands being neglected. Therefore, stress-induced disease is a metabolic prioritization issue, rather than a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/intended-accidental-harm-is-more-permissible-than-intended-harm">direct harmful effect</a> of stress.</p>
